metadata.title: Beechcraft Bonanza
aws::graph::propositions: Notable Flights of the Beechcraft Bonanza
The fourth Beechcraft Bonanza to come off the production line was piloted by Captain William Odom in January 1949.
Captain William Odom flew the fourth Beechcraft Bonanza from Honolulu, Hawaii, to the continental United States in January 1949.
The flight from Honolulu, Hawaii, to the continental United States covered 2,900 statute miles.
The fourth Beechcraft Bonanza was the first light airplane to fly from Hawaii to the continental United States.
The fourth Beechcraft Bonanza was named "Waikiki Beech".
The standard fuel capacity of the Beechcraft Bonanza was 40 gallons (150 L).
The fuel capacity of "Waikiki Beech" was increased to 268 gallons (1010 L).
The increased fuel capacity of "Waikiki Beech" was achieved using fuselage and wing tanks.
The increased fuel capacity gave "Waikiki Beech" a still-air range of nearly 5,000 statute miles.
In March 1949, Captain William Odom piloted "Waikiki Beech" from Honolulu to Teterboro, New Jersey.
The flight from Honolulu to Teterboro, New Jersey covered a distance of 5,273 miles (8,486 km).
The March 1949 flight set a nonstop record.

text:
## Notable flights
In January 1949, the fourth Bonanza to come off the production line was piloted by Captain William Odom from Honolulu, Hawaii, to the continental United States (2,900 statute miles), the first light airplane to do so.  The airplane was called Waikiki Beech, and its 40-gallon (150 L) fuel capacity was increased (using fuselage and wing tanks) to 268 gallons (1010 L), which gave a still-air range of nearly 5,000 statute miles.
In March 1949, Captain Odom piloted Waikiki Beech a distance of 5,273 miles (8,486 km) from Honolulu to Teterboro, New Jersey, setting a nonstop record.
